The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

 Tehelka taint

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 New Delhi, Dec. 22: When the Congress decided to re-induct V. Sreenivasa Prasad, Tehelka seemed a small price to pay for the homecoming of this Dalit leader from Mysore.

 He is valuable to us because he has men and material resources in all the districts, said a source.

 Prasads name figured prominently in the Tehelka videotapes that had embarrassed the NDA, George Fernandes and Jaya Jaitly and gladdened the Congresss heart. Jaya, then a senior leader of the now defunct Samata Party, was allegedly caught telling a fictitious arms dealer money for a certain deal should be given to party treasurer Prasad. 

 Yesterday, when Congress general secretary B.K. Hari Prasad (who belongs to Karnataka) and Praveen Davar, the national secretary in charge of the state, announced Prasads return, they were reminded that the Tehelka sting operation was a major point of their 2004 poll campaign. 

 Davar brushed it aside, saying Prasad was innocent. The news portal later said they were mistaken (about him) and withdrew the charge. 

 Prasad had first joined the Congress in 1979 and was elected MP four times. He then quit the party to join the late Ramakrishna Hegde 




